    "flowchart": {
        "name": "Sloping roofs",
        "description": "A example of how to chop the top of some blocks to make sloping roofs that are still planar.\n\nThe first step is to get the vertices of the roof polygon. The roof polygon is always the last one in the list. \n\n    pg_top = ex[listLen ( ex ) - 1]\n\nThe trick is then to move two vertices that are diagonal to each other either up or down. They must move opposite directions.\n\nSo if I choose vertex 0 to go up, then vertex 2 must go down.\nIf 1 goes up, then 3 goes down.\nIf 2 goes up, then 0 goes down.\nIf 3 goes up, then 1 goes down.\n\nThe first vertex to move is 'a', and it is set by ranomly selecting a number brtwee 0 and 4 (inc 0, but not incl 4). Like this:\n\n    a = randInt ( 0 , 4 )\n\nNow we get the diagonal of this, called 'b', by adding 2. But if that results in a number greater than 3, then we need it to loop around again back to the start. So lets say a = 2, then b = a + 2 = 4. But 4 is greater than 3, and we only have 4 vertices (0, 1, 2, 3). So we need to loop back to the start. So we use the % operator.\n\n    b = (a + 2) % 4\n\nThen I paint my roofs blue :)\n\n\n\n\n",
